values: This week I'm having a really creative artsy feeling that's taken over me. I've painted, drawn and now I'm cooking!!! I want to share with you the recipe that I made this morning called "Warm Strawberry cupcake baked in a teacup". I also call friday's #Cupcakefriday's so watch everyweek for more recipes for cupcakes :) Makes 6 cupcakes Ingrediants: * Butter 8 tbsp, softened plus extra for greasing your teacups *Strawberry Jam 4tbsp * Caster Sugar generous 1/2 cup * 2 eggs lightly beaten * Vanilla extract 1 tsp * Self-raising flour (white) generous 3/4 * Fresh Strawberries 1 tub * Icing sugar (for dusting) Equipment * Egg beaters * Teacups 6 * Bowls * Spoons * Baking tray 1. Preheat oven to 180 degrees C. Grease six heavy round teacups with butter. Spoon in two teaspoons of Strawberry Jam in the bottom of each cup. 2. Put the butter, sugar in a bowl and beat until light and fluffy. Gradually add the eggs and beat well when you've added them, add vanilla extract. Stir in the flour and use a large metal spoon to fold in the mixture. Spoon into your teacups 3. Place your teacups in a pan and pour hot water to cover about an inch of the teacups. Boil water before you start to to mix the batter (so you don't have to wait). Bake the cupcakes in the preheated oven for about 20minutes. Cover your teacups over with tin-foil before you put them in the oven!!! (I learnt the hardway!!!) or until they are golden brown (mine were very brown), insert a skewer into the centre of your cupcake to check if it's cooked, if it come out clean take them out of the oven. LEave them to cool for 2-3minutes, them carefully left them out of the pan and onto the saucers. 4. While you are waiting for the cupcakes to cook, slice the strawberries in half and take of the tops. After the cupcakes have cooled sprinkle some icing sugar onto the tops of the cupcakes to decorate and then place two halves of the strawberries ontop of your cupcakes as decoration. ok, well i've been requested to do a write up about my trip to Canberra, so this is like a brief summary. Well, we drove down there, which took 5 hours which wasn't bad, then when we arrived at the hotel we got dressed again to go visit one of Mum's friends, Nadine. She is this really awesome bohemian woman that teachers ESL in like Morocco, and Vietnam! (even though she doesn't have a degree for it) she does it through the Australian volunteers something....i can't remember, but her stories were amazing, and i totally want to go over there and do what she's doing, 'cause it sounds so exciting! 
and the really cool thing is that she loves France so she had lots of French stories which were cool. 
Yeah, so also we went to the National Gallery of Australia, to see the " Journey to the afterlife ( Egyptian antiques from the Louvre) at the National Gallery of Australia, which was awesome! it was really fascinating how the Egyptians lived, and worked and their really odd gods and stuff. And while i was there, i saw Mrs Brooks , which was strange at first, but then it was cool. Um...Next day we went to Parliament house, that was ok, i'm not really into politics so i was lost most of the time, but Mum wanted to see it, 'cause she said she hadn't been before. We went shopping afterward, and i got some amazing sales (score!) and then we were going to go see "little miss sunshine" at the movies but the it was canceled, so that sucked. And so i wanted to go swimming instead, but there were always people in the pool which was annoying. 
So, on the last day we went to the war museum, which was ok ( it really isn't my seen, but Dad wanted to go see it, so we did) and then we drove home. 
yeah, so i had fun, and got to go see the Egyptian exhibition which i really wanted to see, so it was all good.

hope everyone else is having fun, before we all start the new chapters of our lives soon (FREAKY!!!!)

love, Meredith xx

I'm going away to Canberra for 5 days!
thought you guys may want to know
anyways, see you soon!

love always,
Meredith xx

The Five Love Languages

My primary love language is probably
Words of Affirmation
with a secondary love language being
Quality Time.

Complete set of results

Words of Affirmation: 9
Quality Time: 8
Physical Touch: 6
Receiving Gifts: 4
Acts of Service: 3


Information

Unhappiness in relationships, according to Dr. Gary Chapman, is often due to the fact that we speak different love languages. Sometimes we don't understand our partner's requirements, or even our own. We all have a "love tank" that needs to be filled in order for us to express love to others, but there are different means by which our tank can be filled, and there are different ways that we can express love to others.

Test Results: Introvert: 9%, iNtuitive: 8%, Feeling: 47%, Judging: 40%
Your Personality Type is:

INFJ 
 An INFJ is patient, giving, and insightful. They are known for their depth of caring, their loyalty, and their empathy. INFJs are philosophical thinkers who seek the greater meaning of things, and connect with the bigger picture.

They are very helpful, and enjoy making others happy. They strive for harmony in the world at large, and will often overcome their quiet, shy nature for a worthy cause, or for justice. An INFJ will work tirelessly for something he or she believes in.

INFJs are often described as Mystics or visionaries. They are rarely decieved by the facades of others, and can spot hidden motivations and buried feelings easily. Despite having this ability, an INFJ may have trouble making their own needs known to others, and with being understood.


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

INFJs are quite intellectual and well-read. They have a sly, ironic sense of humor. When they are comfortable enough with their surroundings to let it show, they can even be the life of the party.

INFJs are often very creative, artistic people. They find inspiration in their own rich inner life, and attempt to bring that richness to others through their creativity. Paradoxically, Many INFJs keep their creations closely guarded, for fear of ridicule.

INFJs, more than any of the other Introverted types, need an Extrovert in their lives to bring their insight, creativity, and intentions out into the open. Without an Extrovert, an INFJ will become unhappy very quickly.

Most INFJs have many hobbies. Their hobbies are an important release from the stress of being in tune with the feellings and needs of everyone around them. Hobbies afford an INFJ the quiet time they need in order to rest and re-center themselves.

They usually enjoy reading, and many INFJs like to write too. Topics that INFJs are drawn to include philosophy, poetry, mysticism, and metaphysics. They also tend to like cooking, gardening, and art.


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

INFJs are natural nurturers. They love to keep things running harmoniously and to ensure that their loved ones have what they need. An INFJ is concerned with taking care of everyone around them, and with taking up causes to make the world a better place. INFJs try to avoid insensitive, dishonest, or disingenuous people, but they will practically bend over backwards to accomodate everyone.

INFJs are one of the most kind hearted, gentle, and empathic types, but they tend to put up a wall around themselves in order to avoid being hurt. They only open up to a few very close, highly trusted people.

An INFJ is much more sensitive emotionally than any other type. Because of their sensitivity, they make very good counselors, and they have a special knack with young children. Many kindergarten and daycare teachers, veterinarians, and nurses are INFJs.


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

INFJs have very high expectations of themselves and others, and the same severe dislike of conflict that the all NF types share. INFJs are very modest, and rarely give themselves enough credit.

When they become emotionally exhausted or stressed out, they can start to show some of the negative qualities of an an ESTP, their polar opposite.

An INFJ is compatible with any other iNtuitive type. Their most trouble-free match in a relationship is either an ENFP (Extroverted, INtuitive, Feeling, Perceiving), or an ENTP (Extroverted, INtuitive, Thinking, Perceiving). An INFJ's worst possible match in a relationship is an ESTP or an ESFP.


Extroverts match best with introverts.


INtuitive personality types and Sensor personality types are a completely incompatible match.


Thinking and Feeling are neutral in a relationship.


A free spirited Perceiving personality type needs a buttoned-down Judging personality type to make sure the bills get paid on time, and the kids get their homework done.


A prim and proper Judging personality type needs a laid back Perceiving personality type to bring new opportunities to fruition, to stop them from getting stuck in a rut, and to keep them from taking themselves too seriously.


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

INFJs are the rarest of all the types making up only 1% to 3% of the population in The United States.
